<br>
On our last second floor hate raid (this last Friday) our puller at 61 had a hard time getting the mob to retain aggro and follow with just run3 on.  In fact half the mobs we had to charge as he simply couldnt get them to follow.<br>
<br>
But yes, below around 55 your aggro radius is large enough its possible if there is a mob directly above you.  This is of most concern when running to the west camp as halfway up the wall means your bouncing and that again can aggro the floor.  This is also a question of experience too though.  Our guild often runs with SoE up there because we all know where we're going and are careful to check.  I wouldnt suggest that with KCoG though. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Sow is often a bad idea if your running to west camp from the portal in an unbroken plane.  The simple reason is that you will outrun the mobs, but on the first floor aggro is simple SCREWED and you can easily chain aggro the entire floor to west camp since you might not even know a mob is aggro'd on you.  Suggestion is to remove sow and soe and stop at regular intervals to check for aggro.  I usually do so at the corners.<br>
<br>
Sprite Golems are no longer 100% MR.  With the resist changes, they are about 99% MR.  I've landed 1 snare since the changes.  Frankly, its not worth it.  That snare only landed with a combo of Malo and Tash and I had 7 resisted snares prior to that.  I believe you need Tash to have landed in order for snare to have a chance at sticking.  As the enchanter is generally busy at this point, its rarely happens.  And I believe you need to use the highest level tash, I dont believe the mage version debuffs enough MR.  I'm not sure what our enchanter used, but it might have been the level 60 Winds of Tashanian.  In which case, KCoG might be screwed there.<br>
<br>
But if you have 50+ people there, a running mob usually wont get very far anyway.  Just make sure he's pulled back all the way to camp and not being fought way outside.<br>
<br>
I find it very useful for druids and unengaged shamans to constantly have the enchanter targeted.  Losing your enchanter is usually the kiss of death if you have more than 4 mobs in camp.  In general during the furball while the MA is intially grabbing aggro and the enchanter is still attempting to mez I'll keep the enchanter targeted.  Once it calms down and all mobs are mez'd I'll switch out to nuking.  Then when I see the mob die and the MA begin to target a new mob, I'll again switch out to targeting the enchanter in case the MA fails to gain enough aggro quick enough.<br>
<br>
Regardless of what you hear, there's no such thing as wasted mana when it comes to healing your enchanter or even spot healing the MA.  Especially if there is an abundance of healers in the raid.  Keep your enchanter up at all costs.  Doesnt matter if you are in the group with the enchanter or not.<br>
<br>
What probably got you massive aggro was a few people sitting before the break was complete.  That aggro then chained elsewhere and brought a train.  The worst mob for chain aggro appears to be the Deathrot Knight.  I've literally seen him pull half the zone even though he was standing alone.<br>
<br>
Second floor aggro issues are generally only a problem if you have lev on and are running a bit too high on the wall, or get grav fluxed (with or without lev on).  But due to how aggro works on the second floor, its not that big an issue at the entrance.<br>
<br>
One thing to keep in mind when doing a portal break, is that you dont usually run from the portal to West Camp.  Either you do that initally, or you break at the portal and pull to there to clear the immediate area.  Then the puller works north and pulls till he gets most of that side.  Then the raid runs to the wall and moves up to the house about 2 houses down from the north wall.  Hard to explain without a map.  Then you pull the area surrounding the Maestro's house and any mobs nearby.  Then you move to west camp and finish pulling the mobs around there and to the south west.  Then move over and slap the Maestro.<br>
<br>
Attempting to run to west camp immediately after breaking the portal tends to land you in the worst of both worlds.  As you have to deal with the inital break and clear, and still have to worry about losing people on the run over.<br>
<br>
However, if you are running to west camp and you gain aggro, you need to drop off the wall and move down in the space between the wall and the houses.  This does 3 things.  1) It allows a chance that anyone else running by wont get the aggro.  2) There's less of a risk of your corpse getting trapped in the wall which will require a necro or SK to summon the corpse as that is not something a guide will do if they are following the rules.  Corpses in terrain is valid for all zones other than the planes and VP.  You remain pretty much on your own in those places, although not as much as in VP.  3) It allows the corpse puller to quickly see and identify your corpse, rather than force them to look for an arm or a leg sticking out.<br>
<br>
Having 70+ people at the entrance is one reason I didnt do portal breaks with KCoG.  Its simply too much lag.  I always sent groups to the west camp by the Maestro's house where are least you could spread out some.  It wasnt ideal as you could lost some or many people, but it was a decent compromise.  And camping out to clear any possible aggro usually occupied people's time while the others were running in.<br>
<br>
That second floor ramp is one of the worst spots in the entire zone.  Not only is it fairly heavily patrolled and ringed by static mobs, but that's one of the few places you can gain and hold second floor aggro.  Depending on where you aggro'd it and the pathing you can pull a number of second floor mobs onto you if you ended up by the ramp.  Zellex demonstrated this excellently on one memoriable Hate raid.  Although, that was before we fully understood how chain aggro worked up on the first floor and how second floor aggro could be contained.<br>
<br>
As I think I pointed out elsewhere, you cannot sit at the portal.  Ever, till the wanderers are cleared.  And even then, till you clear the adjacent houses, the only relatively safe sit spot is the left hand corner on the side of the portal house on the opposite side that you came in on.  I think its the SW corner of the house.  You have to stay in that corner, and its best never to sit while in the portal house.  The problem is that you can easily chain aggro.  You sit and accidently aggro a mob next door or perhaps a wanderer.  He comes on in and smacks you down in the best case scenario.  Worst case is he tries to run back, but because of how crappy Hate mob pathing he, he gets lost.  He then transfer aggro to other mobs.  Then your puller pulls one of them and gets the entire deal.  You really have to be careful about sitting on breaks both in Fear and Hate.<br>
<br>
And again, level makes all the difference.  A well equiped level 60 or 61 can get away with sitting in places a similarly equiped level 55 cant.<br>
<br>
Also you puller can retain aggro even after they FD.  Depending on how bad it is on that night, your puller may need to FD after each pull for the first few hours till you clear enough mobs.<br>
<br>
Anyway, it sounds like you have a very good raid overall.  I'm sorry I missed it, but I doubt you would've needed me with that many people.  And being able to take out th Maestro plus friends is no small feat. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
