As for it being all enchanters - if I read correctly on our Guild message boards, at least two of the Rangers in my guild ( Frebxb and Shadowpath ) were able to help out by &quot;peeling and parking.&quot;  We stress and discuss tactics and strategies in our guild, and one that has been talked about on our boards by our proficient Rangers is the &quot;P&amp;P&quot;.  Below is the first post in the &quot;P&amp;P&quot; discussion, written by Shadowpath, a guild ranger who totally amazed me when I saw him in action for the first time.  I hope you don't mind me posting this here, Shadow.  If so, you can flog me later.<br>
<br>
From Shadowpath:<br>
Peeling is a term used originally ( in my experience ) to describe the Rangers role as protector of the enchanter in group situations. When the enchanter ( for whatever reason ) gains the interest of a mob ( ie. aggroes it ), the Ranger quickly moves on over, assists the enchanter to target his or her mob, and WITHOUT ATTACKING ( you must tap the auto attack key off ) taunts and snares the mob in order to &quot; peel &quot; it off and move it away. <br>
<br>
A very important aspect of peeling is to make sure you are not attacking the mob, as the enchanter will not be able to mezz it if you are. Just get its attention long enough for the enchanter to survive and get a mezz off. One good turn deserves another. <br>
<br>
Another method of Ranger peeling I have begun to use more and more often involves providing crowd control when a enchanter is not available. Rangers are EXCELLENT at providing crowd control given a well rounded group. Peeling in this situation goes something like this: Puller brings back multiples. Everyone assists puller to target main mob. Ranger then switches targets and ATTACKS ( as opposed to the above method of peeling ), taunts, and snares the mob, drawing it to a spot away from the group, and root parks it. Attacking the mob to be peeled helps get its attention so that it can be managed more easily. Repeat as necessary.<br>
 <br>
In a great ( mostly guild ) group at the LCY camp in Karnors just last night I was able to peel and root park 5 mobs while the group dealt with the puller's ( who happened to be the main tank as well ) main mob. One celestial remedy from our cleric was needed after engaging these mobs. <br>
<br>
Now, in order to execute good peeling you must know the camp you are in, including the pathing, spawn points, and times of said camps mobs. Arm yourself with this knowledge, and you will know where to safely manuever a mob and park it without adding more critters to the situation. <br>
<br>
Another important aspect of peeling is to be certain other members of your group do not attack anything but the Main Tanks mob. If they do, your job gets more difficult, as they earn a place on the added mobs hate list, thus making it potentially more difficult to get those mobs attention and peel them. <br>
<br>
Whew. Ok. In guild groups, I can see peeling becoming commonplace, especially since we dont have many chanters. So, all of you Rangers out there, practice your Peeling. Note that 2 methods of peeling are mentioned here, and the tactical differences between are simple but extremely important. In one you do not attack, in the other you do. <br>
One more thing. I have a Macro button that says &quot; I am PEELING %T &quot; on the first line, and that casts Ensnare on the second line. I am considering adding a Taunt function to it above the Ensnare line so that taunt is performed and then snare is cast. <br>
